	<body>
		<outline text="July 2021" type="calendarMonth" name="july2021" >
			<outline text="July 26" type="calendarDay" name="26" >
				<outline text="This is Dave here, using this feed for some testing." type="tweet" created="Mon, 26 Jul 2021 16:57:23 GMT" tweetId="1419703408106385410" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1419703408106385410" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
					<outline text="So fart so good." type="tweet" created="Mon, 26 Jul 2021 16:59:34 GMT" tweetId="1419703953986572288" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1419703953986572288" inReplyToId="1419703408106385410" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
						<outline text="Lettuce try another update." type="tweet" created="Mon, 26 Jul 2021 17:01:23 GMT" tweetId="1419704411589316611" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1419704411589316611" inReplyToId="1419703953986572288" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" />
						</outline>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			</outline>
		<outline text="November 2020" type="calendarMonth" name="november2020" >
			<outline text="November 17" type="calendarDay" name="17" >
				<outline text="@thedavidcrosby -- what do you think?? &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1328718548336840704/photo/1&quot;&gt;[link]&lt;/a&gt;" type="tweet" created="Tue, 17 Nov 2020 15:16:02 GMT" tweetId="1328718548336840704" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1328718548336840704" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" />
				</outline>
			<outline text="November 27" type="calendarDay" name="27" >
				<outline text="1/4 I'm sure we've lost a lot in the last four years that we don't yet know about, especially in 2020. But the United States is still the United States. Journalism tends to make it appear worse than it is. In day to day life, at least where I live, things are much the same as" type="tweet" created="Fri, 27 Nov 2020 10:03:21 GMT" tweetId="1332263736690823171" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1332263736690823171" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
					<outline text="2/4 before. The store shelves are still full. You can still buy a wonderful meal. Want to buy a car? You can. The roads are clear. Gas stations have gas. Supply chains work. The health care system is a mess, as before, but much worse right now. The laws for the most part are" type="tweet" created="Fri, 27 Nov 2020 10:03:22 GMT" tweetId="1332263740692193283" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1332263740692193283" inReplyToId="1332263736690823171" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
						<outline text="3/4 enforced (except for you know who and his friends). Western civilization created and tested three highly effective vaccines in record time. We did this. To Americans who hate elites, if you understand these sentences, you might want to think again about living in a country" type="tweet" created="Fri, 27 Nov 2020 10:03:23 GMT" tweetId="1332263744898994177" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1332263744898994177" inReplyToId="1332263740692193283" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
							<outline text="4/4 that values education, science and math enough to get these things done, when needed, to save your life. Yours. You. Now we're going to try to get our political system to work for us again. Maybe you can possibly not get in the way of that? I know that's a lot to hope for. 😀" type="tweet" created="Fri, 27 Nov 2020 10:03:24 GMT" tweetId="1332263749164601347" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1332263749164601347" inReplyToId="1332263744898994177" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" />
							</outline>
						</outline>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="November 8" type="calendarDay" name="08" >
				<outline text="1/3 A big company uses a monopoly in one area to create a monopoly in another. It was the basis for the anti-trust case against Microsoft in the 90s. They were forcing PC manufacturers to bundle their web browser, which was not a monopoly with their operating system, which was," type="tweet" created="Mon, 09 Nov 2020 02:21:07 GMT" tweetId="1325624427363643392" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1325624427363643392" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
					<outline text="2/3 thus forcing the leading browser, Netscape, out of the market. This happens over and over in tech. Google does it by using their monopoly in search to crush competitors in other categories. It can't be allowed. Products must compete on merit, not because we are forced to use" type="tweet" created="Mon, 09 Nov 2020 02:21:07 GMT" tweetId="1325624430828150788" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1325624430828150788" inReplyToId="1325624427363643392" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
						<outline text="3/3 them." type="tweet" created="Mon, 09 Nov 2020 02:21:08 GMT" tweetId="1325624434997268480" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1325624434997268480" inReplyToId="1325624430828150788" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" />
						</outline>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			</outline>
		<outline text="October 2020" type="calendarMonth" name="october2020" >
			<outline text="October 28" type="calendarDay" name="28" >
				<outline text="1/3 A big company uses a monopoly in one area to create a monopoly in another. It was the basis for the anti-trust case against Microsoft in the 90s. They were forcing PC manufacturers to bundle their web browser, which was not a monopoly with their operating system, which was," type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 04:28:02 GMT" tweetId="1321307712504909828" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321307712504909828" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
					<outline text="2/3 thus forcing the leading browser, Netscape, out of the market. This happens over and over in tech. Google does it by using their monopoly in search to crush competitors in other categories. It can't be allowed. Products must compete on merit, not because we are forced to use" type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 04:28:02 GMT" tweetId="1321307716502069248" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321307716502069248" inReplyToId="1321307712504909828" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
						<outline text="3/3 them." type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 04:28:03 GMT" tweetId="1321307720688029696" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321307720688029696" inReplyToId="1321307716502069248" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" />
						</outline>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="October 27" type="calendarDay" name="27" >
				<outline text="1/5 I once lived on a narrow road, so narrow there was barely room for two cars. When approaching an oncoming car on this narrow lane, at first, when I was a newbie to the neighborhood, I’d do the neighborly thing and move over to the right to make room." type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 00:02:26 GMT" tweetId="1321240875587035136" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321240875587035136" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
					<outline text="2/5 Always, the other car wouldn’t budge, so I’d have to pull off the road and slow to a stop. I found this frustrating of course, an example of selfish, Republican-like behavior." type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 00:02:27 GMT" tweetId="1321240879504510977" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321240879504510977" inReplyToId="1321240875587035136" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
						<outline text="3/5 So then I altered my procedure. When I saw a car approaching, I would still move off the to right, but if they didn't mirror my move, I'd veer to the left, directly into their path. This makes my car look bigger, and more of a threat to them." type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 00:02:29 GMT" tweetId="1321240887930822660" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321240887930822660" inReplyToId="1321240879504510977" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
							<outline text="4/5 No need to honk my horn. The action is enough. Immediately, the other car &amp;lt;i&amp;gt;always&amp;lt;/i&amp;gt; moves to the side, and I then move to my side, and we pass each other, both fully on the road, and going at normal speed." type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 00:02:31 GMT" tweetId="1321240896436842504" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321240896436842504" inReplyToId="1321240887930822660" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" >
								<outline text="5/5 I assume these are otherwise good people who are selfish, like most people are, and will see your offer to get out of their way as weakness, and they'll just plow through you. Like Republicans. If you show you are selfish too, they'll negotiate for a win-win." type="tweet" created="Wed, 28 Oct 2020 00:02:32 GMT" tweetId="1321240900585086977" urltweet="https://twitter.com/bullmancuso/status/1321240900585086977" inReplyToId="1321240896436842504" tweetUserName="bullmancuso" />
								</outline>
							</outline>
						</outline>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			</outline>
		</body>
	</opml>
